Sports; Part 3; Page 7; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
322 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THREE FIELD GOALS BY LOHMILLER GIVE WASHINGTON A WIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW ORLEANS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington kicker Chip Lohmiller enjoyed one of his best performances Sunday 
while Morten Andersen struggled through one of his worst. 
</P>
<P>
Lohmiller kicked three field goals and Gerald Riggs scored a touchdown on a 
nine-yard run as the Washington Redskins rallied for a 16-14 victory Sunday 
over the New Orleans Saints. 
</P>
<P>
Andersen, the most accurate kicker in NFL history, missed two field goals, 
including a 36-yarder with 2:34 left to play. He also missed 52-yard kick in 
the third quarter, giving him a 3-7 mark for the season, well off his 78% 
career mark. 
</P>
<P>
"Andersen is too good a kicker for that to happen," Lohmiller said. "He'll 
bounce back. It felt good to come in and kick against him. It felt real good to 
have a game like this and help the team." 
</P>
<P>
Two of Lohmiller's field goals came after Saint turnovers -- a fumble by Eric 
Martin recovered by A.J. Johnson at the New Orleans 29-yard line on the second 
play of the game and a muffed punt by Derrick Shepard in the fourth quarter 
recovered by Dave Harbour on the Saints 18. 
</P>
<P>
Washington (2-2) lost a yard on three tries on the first possession, and 
Lohmiller kicked a 48-yard field goal. The Redskins drove to a first-and-goal 
at the four-yard line after the recovery of Shepard's fumble, but three rushes 
gained three yards, and Lohmiller kicked the winning field goal from 18 yards. 
</P>
<P>
He also hit a 19-yarder in the third quarter when Washington could get only 
nine yards after a first-and-goal from the 10-yard line. 
</P>
<P>
Riggs' touchdown capped a four-play, 66-yard drive in a 10-point third quarter 
for the Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
The Saints' touchdowns were an 11-yard pass from Bobby Hebert to Lonzell Hill 
in the first quarter and a three-yard run by Dalton Hilliard in the second 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Riggs, averaging almost six yards a carry and just under 120 yards a game, was 
held to 50 yards in 18 rushes. He had only 11 yards in 10 carries at halftime 
as New Orleans built a 14-3 lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, New Orleans kicker Morten Andersen reacts to his missed 36-yard field 
goal as Washington's Charles Mann (71) begins celebrating. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
