<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
TEXAS SCHOOL FINANCING UPSET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
AUSTIN, Tex. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Texas Supreme Court, saying "efficient" doesn't mean "cheap," ruled today 
that the state's method of financing schools is unconstitutional and gave 
lawmakers until May to develop a new one. 
</P>
<P>
The nine-member court, however, said it would not instruct the Legislature what 
specific steps to take to correct the problem. 
</P>
<P>
A state district judge had held the school finance system unconstitutional in a 
case brought by poor school districts against the state education commissioner 
and others. That ruling was overturned last December by the U.S. 3rd Circuit 
Court of Appeals, but the high court upheld the plaintiffs today on the ground 
that the Constitution requires "efficiency" in government. 
</P>
<P>
"We hold that the state's school financing system is neither financially 
efficient, nor efficient in the sense of providing for a 'general diffusion of 
knowledge' statewide," Justice Oscar Mauzy's opinion said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
